{"segment_id": "00055", "page_num": 55, "segment": "We’ve covered a lot of background on metrics and analytics in this chapter,\nand your head might be a bit full at this point. You’ve learned:\n\n• What makes a good metric\n\n• What vanity metrics are and how to avoid them\n\n• The difference between qualitative and quantitative metrics, between\nexploratory and reporting metrics, between leading and lagging\nmetrics, and between correlated and causal metrics\n\n• What A/B testing is, and why multivariate testing is more common\n\n• The difference between segments and cohorts\n\nIn the coming chapters, you’ll put all of these dimensions to work on a\nvariety of business models and stages of startup growth.\n\nexe rCise | Evaluating the Metrics you track\n\nTake a look at the top three to five metrics that you track religiously\nand review daily. Write them down. Now answer these questions about\nthem:\n\n• How many of those metrics are good metrics?\n\n• How many do you use to make business decisions, and how many\n\nare just vanity metrics?\n\n• Can you eliminate any that aren’t adding value?\n\n• Are there others that you’re now thinking about that may be more\n\nmeaningful?\n\nCross off the bad ones and add new ones to the bottom of your list, and\nlet’s keep going through the book.\n\nCHAPter 2: How to KeeP SCore\n\n29", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": null, "chapter_title": null, "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "• What vanity metrics are and how to avoid them • How many of those metrics are good metrics? are just vanity metrics?", "l2_summary": "• What vanity metrics are and how to avoid them • The difference between qualitative and quantitative metrics, between\nexploratory and reporting metrics, between leading and lagging\nmetrics, and between correlated and causal metrics exe rCise | Evaluating the Metrics you track • How many of those metrics are good metrics? are just vanity metrics? CHAPter 2: How to KeeP SCore", "prev_page": {"page_num": 54, "segment_id": "00054"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 56, "segment_id": "00056"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["metrics", "what", "many", "chapter", "good", "vanity", "difference", "testing", "more", "business"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "data_science", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["good metric", "vanity metric", "qualitative and quantitative metrics", "exploratory and reporting metrics", "leading and lagging metrics", "correlated and causal metrics", "A/B testing"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["metrics and analytics", "metric evaluation", "business models", "startup growth"], "key_concepts": ["good metric", "vanity metric", "qualitative and quantitative metrics", "exploratory and reporting metrics", "leading and lagging metrics", "correlated and causal metrics", "A/B testing", "multivariate testing", "segments and cohorts"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
