{"segment_id": "00139", "page_num": 139, "segment": "C H A P t E R 1 1\n\nModel Four: Media Site\n\nAdvertising pays for the Internet. It’s so easy to insert advertising into\nonline content that for many companies, ad-based monetization is a\nfallback revenue source, which subsidizes a cheaply priced game or helps\npay for the cost of operating a freemium product. Many websites rely on\nadvertising to pay the bills, but few do it well. Those that do are generally\ncontent-focused, trying to attract repeat visitors who will spend a decent\namount of time on the site and view many pages.\n\nIf your business model most closely resembles a media site, then your\nprimary focus is sharing advertisers’ messages with viewers, and getting\npaid for impressions, click-throughs, or sales. Google’s search engine,\nCNET’s home page, and CNN’s website are all media sites.\n\nAd revenue comes in a variety of formats. Some sites make money when they\ndisplay banners or have sponsorship agreements. Sometimes revenue is tied\nto the number of clicks on ads or to a kickback from affiliates. Sometimes\nit’s simply display advertising shown each time there’s an engagement with\na visitor.\n\nMedia sites care most of all about click-through or display rates, because\nthose are actual revenue, but they also need to maximize the time visitors\nspend on the site, the number of pages they see, and the number of unique\nvisitors (versus repeat visitors who keep coming back), because this\nrepresents inventory---chances to show ads to visitors---and a growing\nreach of new people in whom advertisers might be interested.\n\n113", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "14", "chapter_title": "to understand how your current stage affects the metrics you", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Model Four: Media Site Advertising pays for the Internet. Many websites rely on\nadvertising to pay the bills, but few do it well.", "l2_summary": "Model Four: Media Site Advertising pays for the Internet. Many websites rely on\nadvertising to pay the bills, but few do it well. Those that do are generally\ncontent-focused, trying to attract repeat visitors who will spend a decent\namount of time on the site and view many pages. Ad revenue comes in a variety of formats. Sometimes revenue is tied\nto the number of clicks on ads or to a kickback from affiliates.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 138, "segment_id": "00138"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 140, "segment_id": "00140"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["visitors", "media", "site", "advertising", "revenue", "many", "time", "sites", "display", "number"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Google", "CNET", "CNN"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["click-through or display rates", "time visitors spend on the site", "number of pages they see", "number of unique visitors"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["ad-based monetization", "media sites", "advertising formats", "visitor engagement metrics"], "key_concepts": ["ad-based revenue models", "content-focused websites", "impression and click-through rates"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
