{"segment_id": "00207", "page_num": 207, "segment": "twitter’s Advanced Search\n\nFor startups, Twitter is a goldmine. Its asymmetric nature---I can\nfollow you, but you don’t have to follow me back---and relatively\nunwalled garden means people expect interactions. And we’re vain; if\nyou mention someone, he’ll probably come find out what you said and\nwho you are. Provided you don’t abuse this privilege, it’s a great way\nto find people.\n\nLet’s say you’re building a product for lawyers and want to talk to\npeople nearby. Put keywords and location information into Twitter’s\nAdvanced Search, as shown in Figure 15-3.\n\nFigure 15-3. Using Twitter’s Advanced Search to\nstalk people\n\nYou’ll get a list of organizations and people who might qualify similar\nto the one in Figure 15-4.\n\nNow, if you’re careful, you can reach out to them. Don’t spam them;\nget to know them a bit, see where they live and what they say, and\nwhen they mention something relevant---or when you feel comfortable\ndoing so---speak up. Just mention them by name, invite them to take a\nsurvey, and so on.\n\nThere are other interesting tools for digging into Twitter and finding\npeople. Moz has a tool called Followerwonk, and there’s also the freely\navailable people search engine, Twellow.\n\nCHAPter 15 : StAge one: eMPAtHY\n\n181", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "twitter’s Advanced Search Put keywords and location information into Twitter’s\nAdvanced Search, as shown in Figure 15-3. Using Twitter’s Advanced Search to\nstalk people", "l2_summary": "twitter’s Advanced Search For startups, Twitter is a goldmine. Provided you don’t abuse this privilege, it’s a great way\nto find people. Put keywords and location information into Twitter’s\nAdvanced Search, as shown in Figure 15-3. Using Twitter’s Advanced Search to\nstalk people You’ll get a list of organizations and people who might qualify similar\nto the one in Figure 15-4.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 206, "segment_id": "00206"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 208, "segment_id": "00208"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["people", "twitter", "search", "advanced", "mention", "figure", "follow", "find", "what", "when"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "programming|other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Twitter", "Moz"], "people": [], "products": ["product for lawyers"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Twitter’s Advanced Search", "Followerwonk", "Twellow"], "topics": ["Using Twitter for market research", "Finding potential customers on Twitter", "Tools for Twitter analysis"], "key_concepts": ["Asymmetric nature of Twitter", "Advanced search techniques", "Engaging with potential customers"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": "Utilizing Twitter’s advanced search and other tools to identify and engage with relevant individuals and organizations.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00208", "page_num": 208, "segment": "Figure 15-4. Real customers are just a few tweets\naway\n\nLinkedIn\n\nAnother huge boon to startups everywhere is LinkedIn. You can access\na tremendous amount of demographic data through searches like the\none in Figure 15-5.\n\nYou don’t need to connect to these people on LinkedIn, because you\ncan just find their names and numbers, look up their firms’ phone\nnumbers, and start dialing. But if you do have a friend in common,\nyou’ll find that a warm intro works wonders.\n\nLinkedIn also has groups which you can search through and join. Most\nof these groups are aligned around particular interests, so you can find\nrelevant people and also do some background research.\n\n182\n\nPArt two: FInDIng tHe rIgHt MetrIC For rIgHt now", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Another huge boon to startups everywhere is LinkedIn. You can access\na tremendous amount of demographic data through searches like the\none in Figure 15-5. LinkedIn also has groups which you can search through and join.", "l2_summary": "Real customers are just a few tweets\naway Another huge boon to startups everywhere is LinkedIn. You can access\na tremendous amount of demographic data through searches like the\none in Figure 15-5. You don’t need to connect to these people on LinkedIn, because you\ncan just find their names and numbers, look up their firms’ phone\nnumbers, and start dialing. LinkedIn also has groups which you can search through and join. Most\nof these groups are aligned around particular interests, so you can find\nrelevant people and also do some background research.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 207, "segment_id": "00207"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 209, "segment_id": "00209"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "