{"segment_id": "00319", "page_num": 319, "segment": "C H A Pt E R 2 2\n\nE-commerce: Lines in the Sand\n\nBefore we get into specific e-commerce metrics, we want to reinforce an\nimportant dimension of storefront segmentation.\n\nThere’s a tendency to think of all mobile use as the same. That’s wrong.\n“One of my pet peeves these days is how ‘mobile’ traffic is defined,” says\ninvestor and entrepreneur Derek Szeto. “It’s often defined as tablet plus\nsmartphone, and especially from a commerce perspective, they’re very\ndifferent things. If I were managing a marketplace or storefront, I’d segment\nmy analysis into three groups: desktop, tablet, and smartphone.”\n\nPart of the difference comes from the fact that users engage with the online\nworld in three postures: creation (often on a computer with a keyboard),\ninteraction (usually with a smartphone), and consumption (with a tablet).\nMixing tablets and mobile phones into a single category is a dangerous\nmistake. And people buy more media on a tablet than they do on a PC\nbecause that’s where they consume content.\n\nIn other words: your mileage will vary. It’ll depend on whether you’re an\nacquisition- or a loyalty-focused e-commerce site; on whether your buyers\nare buying from a tablet, a phone, or a desktop; and on a variety of other\nimportant dimensions. The only way you can deal with this is to measure,\nlearn, and segment properly.\n\n293", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "E-commerce: Lines in the Sand “It’s often defined as tablet plus\nsmartphone, and especially from a commerce perspective, they’re very\ndifferent things. If I were managing a marketplace or storefront, I’d segment\nmy analysis into three groups: desktop, tablet, and smartphone.”", "l2_summary": "E-commerce: Lines in the Sand Before we get into specific e-commerce metrics, we want to reinforce an\nimportant dimension of storefront segmentation. There’s a tendency to think of all mobile use as the same. “It’s often defined as tablet plus\nsmartphone, and especially from a commerce perspective, they’re very\ndifferent things. If I were managing a marketplace or storefront, I’d segment\nmy analysis into three groups: desktop, tablet, and smartphone.” And people buy more media on a tablet than they do on a PC\nbecause that’s where they consume content.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 318, "segment_id": "00318"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 320, "segment_id": "00320"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["tablet", "commerce", "mobile", "smartphone", "important", "storefront", "defined", "often", "segment", "three"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Derek Szeto"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["e-commerce segmentation", "mobile traffic analysis", "user engagement"], "key_concepts": ["segmentation of mobile use", "difference in user engagement posture", "importance of proper measurement and segmentation"], "problem_statement": "The problem discussed is the incorrect assumption that all mobile traffic (tablet and smartphone) should be treated as a single category for e-commerce analysis.", "solution_approach": "The solution approach involves segmenting analysis into desktop, tablet, and smartphone categories to better understand user behavior and optimize e-commerce strategies.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00320", "page_num": 320, "segment": "Conversion Rate\n\nIn March 2010, Nielsen Online reported the best conversion rates for online\nretailers, as shown in Table 22-1.*\n\nCompany\n\nSchwan’s\n\nwoman within\n\nBlair.com\n\n1800petmeds.com\n\nvitacost.com\n\nQVC\n\nProFlowers\n\noffice Depot\n\nConversion rate\n\n40.6%\n\n25.3%\n\n20.4%\n\n17.8%\n\n16.4%\n\n16.0%\n\n15.8%\n\n15.4%\n\nTable 22-1. Top e-commerce conversion rates\n\nOther big e-commerce sites such as Amazon, Tickets.com, and eBay saw\nlower conversion rates (9.6%, 11.2%, and 11.5%, respectively).†\n\nThese companies fall into three big categories: catalog sites (which have\na considerable number of offline, printed catalogs driving traffic), retail\ngiants like eBay and Amazon, and gift sites tightly linked to intention, such\nas an online flower shop (people don’t browse flowers casually; they go to a\nflower site with one thing in mind).\n\nMany of Nielsen’s highly-ranked companies fall into the loyalty category\nof online retailers, where you’d expect conversion to be high. Schwan’s\nis an online grocery store; it’s not the type of site that many people will\nbrowse and comparison shop with. Others, like Amazon and eBay, have\nincredibly strong brands that exist in the customer’s consciousness on and\noff the Web. “In my experience, most e-commerce startups selling either\ntheir own product or retailing others’ products can expect conversion\nrates of 1--3% maximum,” says Bill D’Alessandro. “Startups shouldn’t\nplug 8--10% conversion into their models when deciding on the viability of\ntheir business---that’s never going to happen. The three things that propel\nyou from 2% to 10% are seriously loyal users, lots of SKUs, and repeat\ncustomers. And even then it’s a big accomplishment.”\n\n* http:///direct/top-10-online-retailers-by-conversion-ratemarch-2010-12774/\n\n† http:///is-amazons-96-conversion-rate-low-heres-why-i-think-so/\n\n294\n\nPArt tHree: LIneS In tHe SAnD", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 9, "cols": 2, "data": [["Company", "Conversion rate"], ["Schwan’s", "40.6%"], ["woman within", "25.3%"], ["Blair.com", "20.4%"], ["1800petmeds.com", "17.8%"], ["vitacost.com", "16.4%"], ["QVC", "16.0%"], ["ProFlowers", "15.8%"], ["office Depot", "15.4%"]], "markdown": "| Company | Conversion rate |\n|---|---|\n| Schwan’s | 40.6% |\n| woman within | 25.3% |\n| Blair.com | 20.4% |\n| 1800petmeds.com | 17.8% |\n| vitacost.com | 16.4% |\n| QVC | 16.0% |\n| ProFlowers | 15.8% |\n| office Depot | 15.4% |"}], "table_count": 1, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "In March 2010, Nielsen Online reported the best conversion rates for online\nretailers, as shown in Table 22-1.* Top e-commerce conversion rates * http:///direct/top-10-online-retailers-by-conversion-ratemarch-2010-12774/", "l2_summary": "In March 2010, Nielsen Online reported the best conversion rates for online\nretailers, as shown in Table 22-1.* Top e-commerce conversion rates Other big e-commerce sites such as Amazon, Tickets.com, and eBay saw\nlower conversion rates (9.6%, 11.2%, and 11.5%, respectively).† Many of Nielsen’s highly-ranked companies fall into the loyalty category\nof online retailers, where you’d expect conversion to be high. * http:///direct/top-10-online-retailers-by-conversion-ratemarch-2010-12774/ † http:///is-amazons-96-conversion-rate-low-heres-why-i-think-so/", "prev_page": {"page_num": 319, "segment_id": "00319"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 321, "segment_id": "00321"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversion", "online", "rates", "rate", "retailers", "commerce", "sites", "amazon", "ebay", "three"], "content_type": "reference", "domain": "programming|other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Schwan’s", "woman within", "Blair.com", "1800petmeds.com", "vitacost.com", "QVC", "ProFlowers", "office Depot"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["conversion rate"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["e-commerce conversion rates", "online retail performance", "company categories in e-commerce"], "key_concepts": ["conversion rate", "e-commerce performance metrics", "company categorization"], "problem_statement": "Understanding the conversion rates of various online retailers and their business models", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00321", "page_num": 321, "segment": "More typical conversion rates still vary significantly by industry. A 2007\nInvesp post cited FireClick survey data that shows just how different the\nrates can be (see Table 22-2).*\n\nType of site\n\nCatalog\n\nSoftware\n\nFashion and apparel\n\nSpecialty\n\nelectronics\n\noutdoor and sports\n\nConversion rate\n\n5.8%\n\n3.9%\n\n2.3%\n\n1.7%\n\n0.50%\n\n0.40%\n\nTable 22-2. Conversion rates by vertical\n\nOutside of these categories, there seems to be a widely held notion that a\nconversion rate of 2--3% is typical for normal websites. Bestselling author,\nspeaker, and digital marketing expert Bryan Eisenberg has an explanation\nfor where this number may have come from: in 2008, Shop.org claimed that\nits affiliated members had an average within this range, and the FireClick\nindex said the global conversion rate was 2.4%.† Bryan argues that leading\nsites do better because they focus on visitor intent---when you’re going to\nbuy flowers, you’ve already made up your mind; you’re just deciding which\nones. A more recent 2012 study estimated the average conversion rate\nacross the whole Web at 2.13%.‡\n\nBottom Line\n\nIf you’re an online retailer, you’ll get initial conversion rates of around\n2%, which will vary by vertical, but if you can achieve 10%, you’re doing\nincredibly well. If your visitors arrive with a strong intent to buy, you’ll do\nbetter---but, of course, you’ll have to invest elsewhere to get them into that\nmindset.\n\nKevin Hillstrom at Mine That Data cautions that averages are dangerous\nhere. Many electronics retailers, which have a lot of “drive-by” visitors\ndoing research, have conversion rates as low as 0.5%. On the other hand,\nthere’s a correlation between average order size and conversion rate.\n\n* http:///blog/sales-marketing/compare-your-site-conversion-rate-to-ecommercesite-averages.html\n\n† http:///clickz/column/1718099/the-average-conversion-rate-is-it-myth\n\n‡ http:///blog/2012/05/shopping-cart-abandonment/\n\nCHAPter 22: e-CoMMerCe: LIneS In tHe SAnD\n\n295", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 7, "cols": 2, "data": [["Type of site", "Conversion rate"], ["Catalog", "5.8%"], ["Software", "3.9%"], ["Fashion and apparel", "2.3%"], ["Specialty", "1.7%"], ["electronics", "0.50%"], ["outdoor and sports", "0.40%"]], "markdown": "| Type of site | Conversion rate |\n|---|---|\n| Catalog | 5.8% |\n| Software | 3.9% |\n| Fashion and apparel | 2.3% |\n| Specialty | 1.7% |\n| electronics | 0.50% |\n| outdoor and sports | 0.40% |"}], "table_count": 1, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Conversion rates by vertical A more recent 2012 study estimated the average conversion rate\nacross the whole Web at 2.13%.‡ † http:///clickz/column/1718099/the-average-conversion-rate-is-it-myth", "l2_summary": "More typical conversion rates still vary significantly by industry. Conversion rates by vertical Outside of these categories, there seems to be a widely held notion that a\nconversion rate of 2--3% is typical for normal websites. A more recent 2012 study estimated the average conversion rate\nacross the whole Web at 2.13%.‡ * http:///blog/sales-marketing/compare-your-site-conversion-rate-to-ecommercesite-averages.html † http:///clickz/column/1718099/the-average-conversion-rate-is-it-myth", "prev_page": {"page_num": 320, "segment_id": "00320"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 322, "segment_id": "00322"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversion", "rate", "rates", "have", "average", "which", "http", "more", "typical", "vary"], "content_type": "reference", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Invesp", "FireClick", "Shop.org", "Mine That Data"], "people": ["Bryan Eisenberg", "Kevin Hillstrom"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["conversion rates"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["conversion rates by industry", "average conversion rates", "factors affecting conversion rates"], "key_concepts": ["conversion rates vary by industry", "typical conversion rate of 2-3%", "impact of visitor intent on conversion rates"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00322", "page_num": 322, "segment": "Shopping Cart Abandonment\n\nA 2012 study estimated that just over 65% of buyers abandon their shopping\ncart.* Of those who abandon, 44% do so because of high shipping costs,\n41% decide they aren’t ready to purchase, and 25% find the price is too\nhigh. A February 2012 study estimated abandonment at an even higher\n77%.† Improving on abandonment beyond 65% seems to be a challenge,\nbut that doesn’t stop companies from trying:\n\n• Fab.com, a curated catalog site, puts its shopping cart on a timer as a\npressure tactic to convince buyers to complete their transaction: buy\nsoon, or someone else may steal your purchase from you. The site’s\nbrand of exclusivity and its limited, register-first approach to offers are\nactually reinforced by the expiry timer.\n\n• If you start to buy Facebook ads, then abandon the process, the\ncompany sends you a credit toward your first ads to get you restarted.\n\nPrice does seem to be a factor. Listrak might estimate a 77% abandonment\nrate, but that rate dropped to 67.66% on December 14, 2011---a day that\nmany online retailers declared “free shipping day.”‡\n\nKP Elements, which sells skin care products to combat keratosis pilaris (a\ncommon cosmetic skin condition), ran a pricing test where it compared a\n$30 price point plus $5 shipping on the buy page, versus a $35 price point\nfor the same product, with free shipping. Conversion went from 5% to\n10% with that simple change. The prices were identical---$35---but the free\nshipping offer was twice as compelling to customers.\n\nIn 2012, the Baymard Institute looked at 15 different studies of\nabandonment and concluded that an abandonment rate of roughly 66% is\naverage, as shown in Figure 22-1.§\n\n* http:///blog/2012/05/shopping-cart-abandonment/\n\n† http:///2012/02/listrak-77-of-shopping-carts-abandoned-in-last-six-months.\n\nhtml#\n\n‡ http:///2012/02/02/e-retailers-now-can-track-shopping-cartabandonment-daily\n\n§ http://baymard.com/lists/cart-abandonment-rate\n\n296\n\nPArt tHree: LIneS In tHe SAnD", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Shopping Cart Abandonment * http:///blog/2012/05/shopping-cart-abandonment/ § http://baymard.com/lists/cart-abandonment-rate", "l2_summary": "Shopping Cart Abandonment A February 2012 study estimated abandonment at an even higher\n77%.† Improving on abandonment beyond 65% seems to be a challenge,\nbut that doesn’t stop companies from trying: * http:///blog/2012/05/shopping-cart-abandonment/ † http:///2012/02/listrak-77-of-shopping-carts-abandoned-in-last-six-months. ‡ http:///2012/02/02/e-retailers-now-can-track-shopping-cartabandonment-daily § http://baymard.com/lists/cart-abandonment-rate", "prev_page": {"page_num": 321, "segment_id": "00321"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 323, "segment_id": "00323"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["abandonment", "shopping", "2012", "cart", "shipping", "price", "rate", "http", "abandon", "free"], "content_type": "reference", "domain": "other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Fab.com", "Listrak"], "people": [], "products": ["skin care products for keratosis pilaris"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["shopping cart abandonment rate"], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["shopping cart abandonment", "abandonment reasons", "abandonment solutions"], "key_concepts": ["high shipping costs", "customer readiness", "price sensitivity", "free shipping impact"], "problem_statement": "High shopping cart abandonment rates and their causes", "solution_approach": "Strategies to reduce abandonment, such as pressure tactics, incentives for completing purchases", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00323", "page_num": 323, "segment": "Figure 22-1. Meta-studies are so meta\n\nPrice isn’t the only cause for abandonment. Jason Billingsley says that most\nabandonment studies ignore key variables, such as expected delivery date.\n“As more time-sensitive purchases move online, this becomes critical data,”\nhe says. “Retailers must expose estimated arrive dates and not just shipping\nand fulfillment dates.”\n\nBottom Line\n\nSixty-five percent of people who start down your purchase funnel will\nabandon their purchase before paying for it.\n\nSearch Effectiveness\n\nSearch is now the default way for consumers to research and find products,\nfrom their initial investigation of vendors to their navigation within a site.\nWhile this is true in e-commerce, it’s also relevant for media, user-generated\ncontent (UGC), and two-sided marketplaces.\n\nCHAPter 22: e-CoMMerCe: LIneS In tHe SAnD\n\n297", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Meta-studies are so meta Jason Billingsley says that most\nabandonment studies ignore key variables, such as expected delivery date. CHAPter 22: e-CoMMerCe: LIneS In tHe SAnD", "l2_summary": "Meta-studies are so meta Price isn’t the only cause for abandonment. Jason Billingsley says that most\nabandonment studies ignore key variables, such as expected delivery date. “As more time-sensitive purchases move online, this becomes critical data,”\nhe says. “Retailers must expose estimated arrive dates and not just shipping\nand fulfillment dates.” CHAPter 22: e-CoMMerCe: LIneS In tHe SAnD", "prev_page": {"page_num": 322, "segment_id": "00322"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 324, "segment_id": "00324"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["meta", "studies", "abandonment", "says", "dates", "purchase", "search", "commerce"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Jason Billingsley"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["65% of people who start down your purchase funnel will abandon their purchase before paying for it"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["e-commerce abandonment", "expected delivery date importance"], "key_concepts": ["meta-studies", "purchase funnel abandonment rate", "search effectiveness in e-commerce"], "problem_statement": "The issue of purchase abandonment in e-commerce and the need for retailers to provide accurate estimated arrive dates.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00324", "page_num": 324, "segment": "In e-commerce specifically, 79% of online shoppers spend at least 50%\nof their shopping time researching products. Forty-four percent of online\nshoppers begin by using a search engine.*\n\nMobile search traffic is particularly focused on purchasing. Fifty-four\npercent of iOS web traffic is devoted to search, compared to 36% for the\nInternet as a whole---and 9 out of 10 mobile searches lead to action, with\nover half of them leading to a purchase.\n\nBottom Line\n\nDon’t just think “mobile first.” Think “search first,” and invest in\ninstrumenting search metrics on your website and within your product to\nsee what users are looking for and what they’re not able to find.\n\n* See http://blog.hubspot.com/Portals/249/docs/ebooks/120-marketing-stats-charts-and-graphs.\n\npdf for this and many other statistics on search usage. Chikita provided the ioS search\nnumber, and Search engine Land provided the mobile purchase number.\n\n298\n\nPArt tHree: LIneS In tHe SAnD", "source_file": "Lean_Analytics.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "11", "chapter_title": "MoDeL FoUr: MeDIA SIte", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Forty-four percent of online\nshoppers begin by using a search engine.* Mobile search traffic is particularly focused on purchasing. Chikita provided the ioS search\nnumber, and Search engine Land provided the mobile purchase number.", "l2_summary": "In e-commerce specifically, 79% of online shoppers spend at least 50%\nof their shopping time researching products. Forty-four percent of online\nshoppers begin by using a search engine.* Mobile search traffic is particularly focused on purchasing. Fifty-four\npercent of iOS web traffic is devoted to search, compared to 36% for the\nInternet as a whole---and 9 out of 10 mobile searches lead to action, with\nover half of them leading to a purchase. pdf for this and many other stat