od sense of what’s normal for the world, use this\nkind of approach. At least you’ll know what’s normal---and achievable---\nfor your current business. CHAPter 28: wHAt to Do wHen YoU Don’t HAVe A BASeLIne", "prev_page": {"page_num": 374, "segment_id": "00374"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 376, "segment_id": "00376"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["business", "model", "move", "what", "current", "will", "good", "visitors", "have", "normal"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["7% of visitors will subscribe"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["local maxima", "business model", "lean analytics"], "key_concepts": ["diminishing returns", "moving forward", "normal and achievable baselines"], "problem_statement": "How to determine when to move on from a current business strategy or situation.", "solution_approach": "Identifying local maxima, understanding the business model, setting achievable metrics, and deciding when to pivot.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
